---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import CapitalGainsTaxCalculator from "../../../components/CapitalGainsTaxCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Capital Gains Tax Calculator (UK) | HMRC Rules & Allowances"
  description="Estimate your UK capital gains tax liability. Automatically factors in the Annual Exempt Amount and Basic/Higher rate bands."
>
  <main class="flex-grow pt-24 pb-20">
    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        Capital Gains Tax Calculator (United Kingdom)
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Model your potential HMRC tax liability on the sale of assets like shares, factoring in your income band and tax-free allowances.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <CapitalGainsTaxCalculator defaultCountry="UK" />
    </div>

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16 px-4">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Tax Strategy (United Kingdom)</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Understanding UK Capital Gains Tax
            </h2>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-8 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Introduction</h3>
              <p>
                In the UK, Capital Gains Tax is a tax on the profit when you sell (or 'dispose of') something that's increased in value. This calculator helps you estimate your potential tax liability based on current HMRC rules.
              </p>
              <p class="mt-2">
                For a comprehensive guide on minimizing these taxes, check out our <a href="/blog/capital-gains-tax-uk/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">UK Capital Gains Tax Guide</a>.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Key Concepts</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Annual Exempt Amount:</strong> You only have to pay Capital Gains Tax on your overall gains above your tax-free allowance. For the 2024/25 tax year, this is £3,000.</li>
                <li><strong>Basic vs Higher Rate:</strong> The rate you pay depends on whether you are a basic rate or higher rate taxpayer based on your other income.</li>
                <li><strong>Asset Types:</strong> Gains on residential property (not your main home) are taxed at 18% or 24%. Other assets, like shares, are taxed at 10% or 20%. Our calculator defaults to general assets (10%/20%).</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
            
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Methodology</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator subtracts your purchase price from the sale amount to find your total gain. It then deducts the Annual Exempt Amount (£3,000) to find the taxable gain. Next, it determines how much of this taxable gain falls into your basic rate band versus higher rate band, applying 10% and 20% respectively.
              </p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 italic mt-4">
                Source: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/capital-gains-tax" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="hover:text-slate-300 underline">Gov.UK - Capital Gains Tax</a>.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">What is the Capital Gains Tax allowance in the UK?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  For the 2024/25 tax year, the Annual Exempt Amount for individuals is £3,000. You only pay tax on total gains above this amount.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">How much is Capital Gains Tax on shares in the UK?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  If you are a basic rate taxpayer, you pay 10% on your gains (above the allowance). If you are a higher or additional rate taxpayer, you pay 20%.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Internal Links -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Related Calculators</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
              <a href="/tax-loss-harvesting-calculator/uk/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">UK Tax Loss Harvesting Calculator</a>
              <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/uk/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Buy, Borrow, Die Strategy Calculator (UK)</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the Capital Gains Tax allowance in the UK?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "For the 2024/25 tax year, the Annual Exempt Amount for individuals is £3,000. You only pay tax on total gains above this amount."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much is Capital Gains Tax on shares in the UK?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "If you are a basic rate taxpayer, you pay 10% on your gains (above the allowance). If you are a higher or additional rate taxpayer, you pay 20%."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>
</Layout>
